PREAMBLE

This software is published in the spirit of the Open Internet 4.0 movement.
The authors believe that digital tools must respect user sovereignty: devices
must work without continuous corporate permission, data must be portable, and
software must be auditable, repairable, and forkable.

The source code is open for study, personal use, and community contribution.
However, commercial exploitation of this software without the author's
knowledge and consent is explicitly prohibited.

Full manifesto: https://own-net.com/

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

DEFINITIONS

"Software" means the source code, compiled binaries, documentation, and any
associated files distributed under this license.

"Derivative Work" means any work that incorporates, modifies, or is based
upon the Software or any substantial portion of it.

"Commercial Use" means any use of the Software or Derivative Work in which
the person or organization using it has an Annual Gross Revenue exceeding
USD $100,000 (one hundred thousand US dollars), or where the Software or
Derivative Work is directly sold, licensed, or offered as a paid product
or paid service, regardless of the organization's total revenue.

"Annual Gross Revenue" means the total gross revenue of the legal entity
exercising rights under this license, including all affiliated entities
under common ownership or control, during the most recent twelve-month
fiscal period.

"Closed System" means any product, service, platform, or system that:
  (a) implements remote kill switches or requires continuous third-party
      server authorization for basic operation of user-owned devices or
      software, where such authorization can be revoked without the user's
      consent;
  (b) stores user data exclusively in undocumented proprietary formats
      without providing a documented, machine-readable export mechanism
      that the user can invoke at will;
  (c) cryptographically prevents users from inspecting, modifying, or
      replacing the software running on hardware they have purchased;
  (d) monitors or transmits user activity, usage patterns, or personal
      data without explicit, informed, and independently revocable user
      consent.

